metadata.description:
{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Removes all CCs, pitch, channel pressure and program change events from all takes and all tracks in project.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Performs the action "insert empty item" on each selected track.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Export item names and time stamps to a text file\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script creates a text file from selected items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Main Features\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab "exports" item names and positions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab new file is created into script folder\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab created file name is "Exported item list.txt"\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Lua script for warping the positions of MIDI events. The script only affects events in the MIDI editor lane under the mouse cursor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for changing a linear ramp into a parabolic (or other power) curve.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for accelerating a series of evenly spaced notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for changing the curve shape of LFOs.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Select the target events that will be warped (either notes, velocities, CCs, pitchwheel, channelpressure, text or sysex)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Position mouse over the target area (in the case of notes, either the notes area or the bvelocity lane)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab Press the shortcut key\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab Move mouse left/right to warp the selected events' positions, or up/down to warp the values. (This is simiilar to REAPER's "move in one direction only" mouse modifiers.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse movement is not detected accurately (perhaps due to retina display or jerky mouse), the setting "MouseMovementResolution" in the User Area can be increased.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 the responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and editable takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of editable and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which this script can be run:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own shortcut key. In this case, optionally, if drawing curved shapes are required, the script can also be linked to a mousewheel shortcut (alternatively, use the "1-sided warp (accelerate)" script after drawing the ramp.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse", can each be linked to a toolbar button.\line In this case, each script need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" script needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut (as well as a mousewheel shortcut). Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script. For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since this function is a user script, the way it responds to shortcut keys and mouse buttons is opposite to that of REAPER's built-in mouse actions with mouse modifiers: To run the script, press the shortcut key {\i once} to start the script and then move the mouse or mousewheel {\i without} pressing any mouse buttons. Press the shortcut key again once to stop the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Warning\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script will run in the inline MIDI editor, but if there are any overlapping notes in the take, these may transform into extended notes.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Draw linear or curved ramps of CC and pitchwheel events in real time, chasing start values.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An improvement over REAPER's built-in "Linear ramp CC events" mouse action:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If snap to grid is enabled in the MIDI editor, the endpoints of the ramp will snap to grid, allowing precise positioning of the ramp (allowing, for example, the insertion of a pitch riser at the exact position of a note).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab By using the mousewheel, the shape of the ramp can be changed from linear to curved (allowing the easy insertion of parablic shapes).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can optionally chase existing CC values, instead of starting at the mouse's vertical position. This ensures that CC values change smoothly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script inserts new CCs, instead of only editing existing CCs. (CCs are inserted at the density set in Preferences -> MIDI editor -> "Events per quarter note when drawing in CC lanes".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script does not change or delete existing events until execution ends, so there are no 'overshoot remnants' if the mouse movement overshoots the target endpoint.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The events in the newly inserted ramp are automatically selected and other events in the same lane are deselected, which allows immediate further shaping of the ramp (using, for example, the warping or arching scripts).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can optionally skip redundant CCs (that is, CCs with the same value as the preceding CC).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which this script can be run:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own shortcut key. In this case, optionally, if drawing curved shapes are required, the script can also be linked to a mousewheel shortcut (alternatively, use the "1-sided warp (accelerate)" script after drawing the ramp.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse", can each be linked to a toolbar button.\line In this case, each script need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" script needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut (as well as a mousewheel shortcut). Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script. For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To enable/disable chasing of existing CC values, set the "doChase" parameter in the USER AREA at the beginning of the script to "false".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To enable/disable skipping of redundant CCs, set the "skipRedundant" parameter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To enable/disable deselection of other CCs in the same lane as the new ramp (and in the active take), set the "deselectEverythingInLane" parameter. This allows easy editing of only the new ramp after drawing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As an alternative to deselecting only in the target lane, all MIDI in all editable takes can be deselected before drawing, by setting the deselectAllBeforeDrawing parameter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since this function is a user script, the way it responds to shortcut keys and mouse buttons is opposite to that of REAPER's built-in mouse actions with mouse modifiers: To run the script, press the shortcut key {\i once} to start the script and then move the mouse or mousewheel {\i without} pressing any mouse buttons. Press the shortcut key again once to stop the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
}

